   <td class="contentBorder">
      <a name="bmr"></a>
      <p><b>Base Metabolic Rate Formula</b></p>
	  <p>The BMR formula uses the variables of height, weight, age and gender to calculate the Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR).</p>
      <p><a href="http://www.bmi-calculator.net/bmr-calculator/bmr-formula.php">http://www.bmi-calculator.net/bmr-calculator/bmr-formula.php</a></p>
	  <a name="harris"></a>
	  <p><b>Harris Benedict Formula</b></p>
	  <p>The Harris Benedict Equation is a formula that uses your BMR and then applies an activity factor to determine your total daily energy expenditure (calories).</p>
	  <p><a href="http://www.bmi-calculator.net/bmr-calculator/harris-benedict-equation/">http://www.bmi-calculator.net/bmr-calculator/harris-benedict-equation/</a></p>
	  <a name="tdd"></a>
	  <p><b>Insulin Sensitivity Formula</b></p>
	  <p>Insulin sensitivity helps to determine the total daily insulin dose, including the basal insulin, bolus insulin, and correction insulin, your body will need.</p>
	  <p><a href="http://www.diabetesnet.com/diabetes_treatments/insulin_sensitivity.php#axzz13lvOdSQn">http://www.diabetesnet.com/diabetes_treatments/insulin_sensitivity.php#axzz13lvOdSQn</a><br/><a href="http://www.deo.ucsf.edu/type2/diabetes-treatment/medications-and-therapies/type-2-insulin-rx/calculating-insuliin-dose.html">http://www.deo.ucsf.edu/type2/diabetes-treatment/medications-and-therapies/type-2-insulin-rx/calculating-insuliin-dose.html</a></p>
	  <a name="500"></a>
	  <p><b>500 Rule Formula</b></p>
	  <p>The 500 Rule is based on the assumption that the average person consumes (via meals and snacks) and produces (via the liver) a total of about 500 grams of carbohydrates daily. By dividing 500 by your total daily insulin dose you can get a reasonable approximation of your carb ratio.</p>
	  <p><a href="http://www.diabetesnet.com/diabetes_control_tips/carb_factor.php#axzz193XKfN1p">http://www.diabetesnet.com/diabetes_control_tips/carb_factor.php#axzz193XKfN1p</a><br/><a href="http://www.deo.ucsf.edu/type2/diabetes-treatment/medications-and-therapies/type-2-insulin-rx/calculating-insuliin-dose.html">http://www.deo.ucsf.edu/type2/diabetes-treatment/medications-and-therapies/type-2-insulin-rx/calculating-insuliin-dose.html</a><br/><a href="http://www.mendosa.com/insulin_carb_ratios.htm">http://www.mendosa.com/insulin_carb_ratios.htm</a></p>
	  <a name="1800"></a>
	  <p><b>1800 Rule Formula</b></p>
	  <p>The 1800 Rule shows how far your blood sugar is likely to drop per unit of insulin when administering a correction bolus.</p>
	  <p><a href="http://www.diabetesnet.com/diabetes_control_tips/corr_factor.php#axzz193oa6Z67">http://www.diabetesnet.com/diabetes_control_tips/corr_factor.php#axzz193oa6Z67</a><br/><a href="http://www.deo.ucsf.edu/type2/diabetes-treatment/medications-and-therapies/type-2-insulin-rx/calculating-insuliin-dose.html">http://www.deo.ucsf.edu/type2/diabetes-treatment/medications-and-therapies/type-2-insulin-rx/calculating-insuliin-dose.html</a></p>
	  <a name="basal"></a>
	  <p><b>Basal Insulin Formula</b></p>
	  <p>The Basal Insulin formula is based on the observation that most insulin dependent diabetics find their control is best when their basal insulin makes up about 50% of their total daily insulin dose.</p>
	  <p><a href="http://www.diabetesnet.com/diabetes_control_tips/basal_bolus.php#axzz19445ul3h">http://www.diabetesnet.com/diabetes_control_tips/basal_bolus.php#axzz19445ul3h</a><br/><a href="http://www.deo.ucsf.edu/type2/diabetes-treatment/medications-and-therapies/type-2-insulin-rx/calculating-insuliin-dose.html">http://www.deo.ucsf.edu/type2/diabetes-treatment/medications-and-therapies/type-2-insulin-rx/calculating-insuliin-dose.html</a></p>
